(700, 5, '2016-01-29 17:04:30', '2016-01-29 17:04:30', '<p style="text-align: center;">When it comes to eating healthier and trying to consciously make an effort to do so, meal planning is where it''s at. People get intimidated by the idea, and assume that it will be too hard, when meal prepping is pretty simple, all you have to do is just START. Just like you are taking the time to read this article, in order to make a change in your diet you must find the time to meal prep. Follow these steps and then get ready to welcome the improved, happier, and healthier you! Lets get started!</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">To help you begin, we’ve broken down some of the basics. These practice exercises will help you map out your next week of healthy meals.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://www.prolinekitchenblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Step-11.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-165 " src="http://www.prolinekitchenblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Step-11.jpg" alt="Step 1" width="695" height="421" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Our eating situations always change from week to week  due to different work schedules, after school activities, evening commitments, travel–the list goes on. Here are some things to consider as you assess your eating situation..</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;"><strong>How many meals you need to plan for  </strong>Think about what activities or events you may have going on next week. This will help give you a rough idea of how many meals you’ll need to get through the week, and how many meals you can get from each recipe.</li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;"><strong>What you have time for </strong>Crazy busy weeks are common for many of us and making a mental note to be on the lookout for quick,  slow cooker or make-ahead meals that can be served up in a hurry is crucial. We’re big fans of the cook once, eat twice (or thrice) approach.</li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;"><strong>Your food mood  </strong>Things like the weather, a change in seasons, and food cravings can impact what sounds good on any given day. Thinking about these things beforehand will make the recipe selection process faster and meal times easier on everyone.</li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;"><strong>Your grocery budget</strong> If you want to eat better for less (and who doesn’t) think seasonal produce and sales.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>MEAL PLANNING PRACTICE: PLAN YOUR WEEKLY EATS</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong><a href="http://1y2u3hx8yml32svgcf0087imj-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/map_eats-e1418933125655.png">\r\n</a>1. Grab a pen and paper. </strong>Write the days of the week on the left side of the page and the meals you want to plan across the top.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>2. Sketch out your weekly eats. </strong>Vague descriptions like <em>quick dinner, leftovers,</em> or <em>packable lunch</em> are fine for now. Don’t forget to plan for leftovers and make note of special dietary restrictions here as well.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>3. Tally them up. </strong>Note how many meals you’ll need, grouping together similar ones. For example: <em>2 quick dinners, 3 packable lunches</em>…</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://www.prolinekitchenblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/step-21.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-167 size-full" src="http://www.prolinekitchenblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/step-21.jpg" alt="step 2" width="735" height="886" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Now the fun part! Once you know how many meals you’ll need, it’s time to find some healthy recipes and fill in your calendar for the week. Here are some tips to help.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Create a master recipe list</strong> Having a list of go-to meals is one of the easiest ways to expedite the meal planning process. Consider trying one or two new recipes and use a few old favorites to fill in the gaps. Every time you find a new meal you love, add it to the rotation!</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Find a few new dishes to try</strong> Finding delicious, healthy recipes isn’t hard–you just need to know where to look. Health-conscious cookbooks and food magazines are great but the internet can literally provide millions of healthy recipes at your fingertips.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Some of our favorite websites for healthy recipes include:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul style="text-align: center;">\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://cookinglight.com/?xid=myfitnesspal" target="_blank">Cooking Light</a></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://www.foodnetwork.com/healthy.html" target="_blank">Food Network – Healthy</a></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://www.cleaneatingmag.com/" target="_blank">Clean Eating</a></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;"><a title="The Top 14 Workouts of 2014" href="http://eatingwell.com/" target="_blank">Eating Well</a></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;">Healthy food blogs like <a href="http://skinnytaste.com/" target="_blank">Skinnytaste</a>, <a href="http://www.eatingbirdfood.com/" target="_blank">Eating Bird Food</a>, <a href="http://www.katheats.com/" target="_blank">Kath Eats</a>, <a href="http://www.cooksmarts.com/cs-blog/" target="_blank">Cook Smarts</a>, and <a href="http://fannetasticfood.com/" target="_blank">Fannetastic Food</a>–just to name a few</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Save and organize your recipes</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><em><strong>For online recipes:  </strong></em></p>\r\n\r\n<ul style="text-align: left;">\r\n	<li>Make a folder on your computer specifically for your recipes and organize them so they will be easy to find.</li>\r\n	<li>Create a healthy recipe Pinterest board.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong style="font-style: italic;">For paper recipes:</strong>\r\n<ul style="text-align: center;">\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;">A simple, three-holed binder with some plastic sleeve inserts are great for organizing recipe cards and meals pulled from magazines</li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: left;">Use bright colored tabs to flag favorite cookbook recipes</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://www.prolinekitchenblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/recipe-planning-with-purpose1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-176 size-full" src="http://www.prolinekitchenblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/recipe-planning-with-purpose1.jpg" alt="recipe planning with purpose" width="580" height="580" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Create your meal calendar </strong>Regardless of what format you prefer, the key here is to fill in your calendar with specific meals. Good meal planning is like putting together a puzzle. Try to avoid selecting different recipes that don’t fit together or else you’ll be buying a lot of different ingredients. Select one, look at the ingredient list and let that help you select recipe #2, and so on.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Write your grocery list</strong> Save yourself some time and write your grocery list while you fill out your calendar. Don’t forget to jot down quantities for each ingredient. Before you head to the store take a quick inventory of what you have on hand and cross off the ingredients you don’t need to purchase.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>MEAL PLANNING PRACTICE: COLLECT &amp; CALENDAR YOUR RECIPES</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>1. Start a master recipe list.</strong> Digital versions (like a note on your smartphone) are handy, easy to update and usually within arm’s reach!</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>2. Fill in your calendar.</strong> Pick some favorites from your master list and 1 or 2 new recipes to try.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>3. Write your grocery list.</strong> While doing that, jot down ingredients for each recipe.<strong> </strong>Then, take stock of what you already have on hand before heading to the store.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>4. Pick a time to shop.</strong> Once your shopping is done, you’re ready to tackle food prep. Stay tuned for our how-to post coming up next week.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Got some meal planning tips and tricks of your own to share? Leave them in the comments below!</strong></p>', 'A Beginners Guide to Healthy Meal Planning', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '164-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-01-29 17:04:30', '2016-01-29 17:04:30', '', 164, 'http://www.prolinekitchenblog.com/164-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
